The Setup 

We start from the classical Hamilton function
 
describing an infinite collection of oscillators, labeled by 
, with -dependent coupling. We want to understand the late time 
behavior at large , if at  we excite the zeroth oscillator 
highly into the non-linear regime. The numerics indicate that all other
oscillators remain weekly excited during the decay process, so that we 
may linearize around the minimum of . Furthermore, for large ,
the zeroth oscillator is weakly coupled to all the other ones (the
other oscillators are strongly coupled as ). Accordingly, we 
split the Hamilton hamilton2  into three pieces
 
where  describes the zeroth oscillator that we want to excite,
 
 describes the remaining oscillators linearized around
the minimum, which for convenience we assume to be at ,
 
and . Finally,  describes
the coupling between  and 
 
At this level, the equations of motion are
 

Our strategy is as follows. We intend to treat the RHS of the first two
equations in eqmot2  as a perturbation. Without this term, the first
line can be trivially integrated. By our assumptions on the potential ,
the solution, which we call , will be periodic, and we call 
the corresponding frequency , where 
is the action variable. We then feed this oscillation into the last two 
equations of eqmot2 , which we write as
 
where  is the linear operator
 
supplemented with appropriate boundary conditions (see below). We can
view radiate  as a radiation problem with  as
the source. It is then natural to decompose  into Fourier
modes,
 
and to first compute the energy radiated into the continuum modes of  by
a harmonic source. Summing over all Fourier modes, this will give an
estimate for the rate of energy loss of the zeroth oscillator due to the
coupling to the continuum modes. The expectation is that for large
, the energy loss per period is small, so that the coupling to
the continuum essentially amounts to adding a friction term for , 
with dissipation rate depending on the remaining energy. One can in 
principle study the resulting one-dimensional dissipative system, but 
we have not done this here. On the other hand, for small , in 
particular , the energy loss per period will become 
comparable to . In fact, this will give an estimate for the critical 
. 

Most of what follows is concerned with the operator . In the following
section , we will diagonalize , which means finding the
generalized eigenfunctions and in particular their asymptotics at .
This will allow in section  to compute the power radiated
into the continuum by a harmonic source. Finally, we estimate the Fourier 
coefficients of  to obtain a decay rate of the soliton.


The operator  

The operator  defined by Aop  has the form of a discrete version 
of the familiar class of Sturm-Liouville operators, and we will draw on some 
of the theory pertaining to the latter (see, for instance,).
First, however, we will obtain some elementary results on the nature of
the spectrum of .

The spectrum of  is unbounded and absolutely continuous 

We have
 
The spectrum of  is equal to  and purely absolutely
continuous.
The first part of the statement is easy to prove. Recall that the spectrum
of ,
 
on  is equal to . The spectrum is absolutely 
continuous and the generalized eigenvectors are  
with spectral parameter .

