To prove absolute continuity, there are two possible strategies. The
first is to construct, for given , the generalized
eigenvectors as solutions of the difference equation , 
and to show that these solutions do not grow exponentially as .
We will find these eigenfunctions in subsection  below.
The second method uses the so-called positive commutator method or Mourre theory
. The point of Mourre theory is that one can prove absolute 
continuity of parts of the spectrum of a self-adjoint operator such as  
by simply exhibiting another self-adjoint operator  such that the commutator 
 is positive on the part of the spectrum in question.

