The decay rate of the NC soliton 

As explained in section , the total decay rate of the NC 
soliton is obtained by decomposing the oscillation  
into Fourier modes, fourier , using Pthree  for each mode, 
and summing over Fourier modes, ,
 
where
 
are the Fourier coefficients of . The precise values
of the  of course depend on the details of the potential and the 
exact value of the basic frequency  (which, if we enforce energy 
conservation, is not fixed), so that we need an estimate to make further
progress on total .

There are two regimes in which one can estimate the Fourier coefficients.
The first is for almost harmonic oscillations, for which one can use 
perturbation theory to determine the . This will be the description 
when, for late times, the zeroth oscillator is in a small vicinity 
of the stationary point, and the soliton has almost completely decayed. 
The second regime is defined by . It describes the 
initial stages of the decay of the NC soliton, and it will be a consistent approximation if the 
energy loss per period is much smaller that the total energy in the 
zeroth oscillator, , we require
 
In this regime, the coefficients coeff  can be estimated as 
follows.

If the energy  is exactly equal to the critical value
, there is not only the static solution,
but also the separatrix solution that is not periodic, but
rather takes an infinite amount of time to fall off and come
back to the top of the potential. We call this separatrix
. 

